The original study literally used mice who instinctively form harems and who kill the offspring of rivals. That is not universal primitive human behaviour. Calhoun could have used monogamist mice, but didnt. The mouse city was badly designed because it had a 50:50 female/male ratio, and with no secluded spaces (as would be in nature) for moms to hide their babies from killers. If you want to make a point that humans are also struggling against their instincts in cities, you need to outline exactly which instincts. Which Calhoun did not do, and our instincts are not mapped exactly to forming harems or killing babies, so you would be reaching pretty far into merely speculating. Plus, we have this thing called urban design, Calhoun could have designed the city differently but he didnt because he didnt bother to think about the social dynamics of mice (beyond the fact that animals need food anf shelter). In the end, he didnt even make a point about cities being unsuited to innate instincts either, he simply blamed overcrowding

It's bad experiment design, because you cant use baby-killing mice, and then design no secluded spaces, and then solely blame overcrowding. If the point is that cities need to have sufficient private spaces, dont use baby-killing mice (which btw also add the stress of the male mice constantly fighting each other to form harems) that overbreed. If the point is that cities dont work at all because the place will always overpopulate, that isnt even true given actual human urban demographic trends over time. Even in a problematically overpopulated city like Hong Kong, there are secluded private spaces, the issue is the size of those spaces for the poorest of the city, and many cities are not Hong Kong tier. Calhoun added too much noise and confounding factors. It's not all about having private spaces either, when we consider human (and not rat) behaviour, there's a large benefit both psychologically and even immunologically to interacting with greenery and that's an entirely separate issue unexplored in the mouse experiments, but which some cities have been trying to tackle by including green spaces and various parks within the city as well as encouraging people to take weekend trips into the countryside.

on a more reasonable side i like the pre younger dryas early civilisation theory.

the five minute/last thursday though experiment seem trivial to me: if the forgery of the past is perfect to a quantum level, it effectively exists identicaly in full to a real history, as it extrapolates backwards fully, including past conciousness.

occams razor is not an issue, as what if scenarios deliberately ignore that one.

but in real life learni g from what if scenarios, occams razor is very necessary to prevent near impossible a priori claims from seeping through, like saying everybody is against you just for you (which would require a high degree of dissonance in everybody to uphold such a strange onsided focus, to the degree of them not being able to function with reality, meaning all would die soon.). a lack of occams razor/ a priori critique/ extrapolated-mental-gymnastic-toll-analysis leads to paranoia very quickly.

Have you ever seen a fruit or vegetable in your refrigerator that's a little old? Not inedible, but past the freshness where it'd be at its best. You could eat it but it'd be a little soft and you might have to cut out a bad spot or two. It would just feel like a disappointment to eat, or it feels like too much effort to cut out the bad parts. So instead you just pretend that you don't see it, close the refrigerator, and go back to whatever else you were doing. You tell yourself that you'll get to it later, or maybe you just try to forget that it's even there.

But it doesn't get any better. The long it sits in your refrigerator, the more it decays, the more the little blemishes that put you off grow, the more effort it will take to cut them out, and the less you'll have left. Maybe you'll come back to it later in a worse state and wish you'd eaten it when it today, but more likely you'll just keep ignoring it until it's so rotten that your only choice is to throw it out.

This is the state of your lives right now. Stop lying to yourselves and make a choice, because now is the best shape you'll be in to transition for the rest of your life.

Overcoming Anxiety Edition
previous: >>28815553

Goal of the thread: Reach out to an online contact today.
Keeping up conversations is hard, but remember sometimes it is more about spending time together than it is about the topic!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

I on my own cannot gauge the quality for a lot of the resources, if
anything below is unhelpful, please let me know.

resources (under construction):
Exercise, diet, weight loss/gain: >>>/fit/17018018 (sticky)
NIMH brochures on mental health topics (Depression, BPD, ADHD, etc): https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications
ED: https://www.eatingdisorderhope.com/treatment-for-eating-disorders
General advice from Anons: https://0x0.st/onFZ.txt

currently we lack (mental) health resources.
Suggestions and debate for which to include encouraged!

Additional resources:
Get started with weight loss (courtesy of /fit/fat/):
>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

A few short overview videos (need review by other anons):
Common Sources of Misery: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LO1mTELoj6o

Apart from the goal of the day, here are a few things you can do _today_ to make your life a little better. Keep a diary and write down every success. Some you may do as often as you please, but write down each one individually! You deserve it! Do not feel pressured to do all, but feel free to select one or two!

- Open your window for 10-20 minutes
- pick up items on the floor for 5 minutes
- write down one thing you are grateful for (from abstract things to something like a cute image you saw)
- if you have a bad habit, try making it more inconvenient (putting things in hard to reach places for example)
- do the dishes for 3 minutes
- eat a meal

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>28838340
Bad idea, generally speaking. Intermittent fasting is a thing, but what is much more important than eating little is measuring. Measuring, measuring, measuring. Get a set of kitchen scales and record your ingredients as you are cooking. You can comparably easily achieve 1-2lb/week with comparably little discomfort if you have a high BMI, and 1-.5lb if you are moderately overweight. As a good start, check your TDEE and bodyfat% (see >>28833216). I can make more suggestions from that.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>28838340
You would have to fast way longer than that to do anything to your diet long term, so focus on fixing your diet first and then worry about fasting. Fasting is great ime but it's nothing like the magic pill that everyone online would have you believe it is. It's very intense and takes a surprising amount of effort and planning once you feel how different your body and mind feels in a truly fasted state.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>28838340
fasting is only helpful if you are commiting to it for an extended period, i.e. fasting for multiple weeks. a single week of fasting will make you lose weight, but it will mostly just be muscle and water weight, not fat which is what you are likely after. just buy a bunch of bulk ingredients and start getting into the habit of preparing food for yourself before you worry about fasting, especially if your issue is fast food cravings.

>>28839698
Just ride it out and see how you feel about it?
Yeah, you are going to get different outcomes than a youngshit or midshit, but if you made it as far as an HRT prescription, you've probably got the persistence to just see how it turns out.
I think the mood and brain-related effects of HRT are a bit exaggerated, but they do help. You might feel less stressed about lost time and stuff if your mental health improves a bit.

And if you stick with it long enough, you start to "forget" pre-transition life. Like, after being fully transitioned for like five years, not even passing at all, I forget there was a time I presented as male. Can't remember the last time I went into a men's changing room. Can't remember the last time I ticked off "Male" on a form. Can't remember what I looked like pre-transition without a photograph (and why would I keep photos of that).
Even if you transitioned late, there's just such a mental break between pre and post transition that you'll get far enough away from that inflection point and it won't even be in the rear view mirror anymore.

Look up the double empathy problem. It's not that autists are inherently unempathic, it's that we're bad at empathy with NTs, and NTs are bad at empathy with us. Autist-to-Autist and NT-to-NT communication are equal in terms of understanding/empathy. Autist-to-NT and NT-to-Autist communication score much lower in terms of empathy.
